      "solution": "word = input()\n\nreverse = word[::-1]\n\nprefix = \"\"\nfor i in range(len(word)):\n    if word.startswith(reverse[i:]):\n        prefix = reverse[:i]\n        break\n\nsuffix = \"\"\nfor i in range(len(word)):\n    if word.endswith(reverse[:len(word)-i]):\n        suffix = reverse[len(word)-i:]\n        break\n\nif len(prefix) <= len(suffix):\n    print(prefix + word)\nelse:\n    print(word + suffix)",
      "statement": "A palindrome word is a word that can be read the same forwards and backwards.\nGiven a random string, your goal is to transform it into a palindrome by adding the <<smallest possible number of characters>> either at the <<beginning (prefix)>> or at the <<end (suffix)>> of the word.\nIf both options require the same number of characters, prefer adding the <<prefix>>.\nThis palindrome is called the \"<<minimal palindrome>>\".",
